### 5. DMMF Type Usage Details

Based on examining the actual DMMF types at `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775388078215-q8qn45/packages/dmmf/src/dmmf.ts`:

- All DMMF types are wrapped in `ReadonlyDeep<>`, so all properties are deeply readonly. The template functions receive readonly data -- no mutation needed, just reading.
- `DMMF.Document` has: `datamodel`, `schema`, `mappings`. We only use `datamodel`.
- `DMMF.Datamodel` has: `models: Model[]`, `enums: DatamodelEnum[]`, `types: Model[]`, `indexes: Index[]`.
- `DMMF.Model` has: `name`, `fields: Field[]`, `primaryKey`, `uniqueFields`, `uniqueIndexes`, etc.
- `DMMF.Field` has the comprehensive set at lines 71-101 of dmmf.ts.
- `DMMF.FieldDefault` is `{ name: string, args: Array<string | number> }`. For `@default(autoincrement())`, the DMMF produces `{ name: "autoincrement", args: [] }` (confirmed in snapshot at line 44-47).
- `field.default` can also be a scalar value directly (e.g., `false` for `@default(false)`) as `FieldDefaultScalar` (line 108).

The `hasAutoIncrementDefault` check must handle the union type: `field.default` is `FieldDefault | FieldDefaultScalar | FieldDefaultScalar[] | undefined`. We first check `hasDefaultValue`, then check if `default` is an object with `name === 'autoincrement'`.

